“Finishing second in the Olympics gets you silver. Finishing second in politics gets you oblivion.”

You watch Cronkite read the returns as they come in. You watch as states that your campaign classified as ensured are deemed too close to call. Connecticut is called for Clement, as is New York, and Pennsylvania. Hearing Cronkite call a state blue is listening like nails on a chalkboard, you think to yourself. Your eyes dart to your native California, where Clement narrowly leads you. All that time you put into that pitiful state, and this is how they reward you? You stand up from your seat in order to pace around the hotel room, but you barely get a few steps away from the TV when you hear it: “CBS can now project that Governor Frank Clement of Tennessee has won California, and therefore the Presidency.”

The world slowly goes numb around you. You vaguely feel Pat’s hand on your shoulder, but all you can do is stare at the floor, head supported by your fists. How the hell could this happen? Cuba, the economy, the fact that Frank goddamned Clement, the booze-chugging Southern fool was your opponent, all of those cards were in your deck. Despite the gaffes, the Civil Rights controversy, all of it, your advisors told you that you would be fine. 1948 was a one-off, they said, and yet you stand here as a loser once again. Cursed to forever never be allowed a happy ending. You pour yourself a glass of whiskey and decide to look out the balcony for some time.

The next few years are a blur. Clement fails to pass anything significant, if you remember correctly. Some murmurs surface that you’ll try to run again, but you refuse. Some more years pass. Eventually, the announcer of the Peace Prize comes out. ‘‘For his remarkable work with the Nixon Center in providing food, shelter, and peace for those around the globe, we are pleased to announce that our winner this year is former President of the United States, Richard Milhous Nixon.’’

Maybe there are things more valuable than the Presidency.

EXCERPT FROM THE GENERAL SECRETARY’S SPEECH, REVOLUTION DAY

I gotta tell you, folks, I was probably like 24 or 25, and that's when the whole Republic thing went down the drain. Nixon, he just stayed in the big chair during the last Presidential after he killed the 22nd. Now, everyone's saying he rigged '64 and '68, but let me tell you, power moves are part of the game, right? The elite had to flex a little muscle after the Dems bit the dust in the ‘66 midterm. It was a power party for the bastard.

But here's the real kicker. The real problem That took a while to show its face. Believe me, it wasn't evident right away, even to me. We were in for a ride, a real wild one, but nobody saw it coming back then.

So, you know, Nixon, with probably a little nudge from Kissinger - these guys, they decide to crank up the Vietnam War. And what do they do? They loosen the draft, pulling in millions of beautiful, hardworking Americans into a war that, let's be honest, wasn't exactly the people's choice. It's like they're playing a big game, making us fight a war just to line the pockets of those imperial overlords. Unbelievable, right? I mean, who benefits from all this chaos? It's not the everyday folks, I'll tell you that much. It's all about those suits looking to make a quick buck while the rest of us are left dealing with the consequences.

So there I was, folks, a young guy, just like many of you, when they sent me this letter. Can you believe it? The draft. Me! Now, I've always been a winner, a champ, but suddenly they're telling me, “sir, you've gotta go fight in Vietnam.” I said, “Come on, you're kidding, right?” But you know me, always ready for a challenge. So, I put on the uniform, went through all the drills, became the best soldier they'd ever seen. I was like a one-man army, believe me. The generals, they loved me. It’s all about the drills, right? They'd say, “sir, you're doing a tremendous job with the drills, the best job anyone's ever done.”

You know, folks, as I fought with the utmost valor in that war, I started to see things differently. I looked around and thought, “Wait a minute, I come from a pretty comfortable background, don't I?” I mean, we had buildings, we had money - it was all very bourgeois, very high-class. My old man, God rest his soul, he was part of that system. He was a tough guy, a real go-getter, but he played the game. He did what he had to do to succeed, and I respect that. But I started to realize that maybe, just maybe, the common man wasn't getting a fair shake.

I barely had time to properly analyze that idea when the news came in. I'm out there in the thick of Vietnam, doing my duty, when word comes in. Lodge, Scott, Halleck, Aiken - gone, just like that. An explosion at the Capitol, can you believe it? It was chaos, and suddenly, Nixon is sitting in the big chair unopposed.

Tricky Dick, I like to call him Tricky Dick, starts pointing fingers. Can you believe it? He's out there, blaming the North Vietnamese for the whole assassination plot. A year later, they decide to move me a few kilometers away from Hanoi. Why? Well, they say it's to prepare for a ground assault on the city. The tension in the air was palpable. We're getting ready for something big, and the uncertainty is weighing on everyone. That’s why the sudden boom from the distance on that one fateful morning is something that no one in my detachment could’ve seen coming.

I look up, and there it is – a mushroom cloud rising over Hanoi. I couldn't believe my eyes. The shockwave hit, and I'm thinking, “Did we just nuke the place?” It was surreal, like something out of a nightmare. The devastation was unreal, and I'm standing there, witnessing history.

After the whole nuking, word comes down that we're getting pulled out. Withdrawn, just like that. It turns out, the nuking did its job, or at least that's what they were saying. North Vietnam, they claimed, was toppled. The powers that be decided we didn't need to be there anymore. The bourgeois accomplished what they needed to: destroy the will of the common man on yet another continent and establish yet another capitalist dictatorship. Sadly, many such cases!

After all that Vietnam, uh, stuff, I found myself back home, and something had shifted. The high life, the glitz and glam - it just didn't feel right anymore. I felt like a real worker, real proletariat, you know? So, what did I do? I hopped on a motorcycle and hit the open road.I wanted to see the real America, away from the glitz and glam of the high life.

Along the way, I stumbled upon these small towns with hardworking folks, the backbone of the nation. In one town, I meet this farmer who's battling to keep his family farm going. This big man, strong man, came up to me, tears in his eyes, saying, “sir, I can’t afford to pay my bills”. Another time, I come across a beggar named George Mc, uh, Mc-something. He was a former politician who was removed from Congress after criticizing Nixon for letting the Russians and Chinese nuke each other.

Eventually, I run out of gas in Burlington, Vermont. I wander around for a few hours, looking for a station, until I happened to stumble upon a flier advertising some sort of underground speech. I notice the red hammer and sickle underneath the name of the speaker, Bernard something, and almost walk past it, but something just draws me to it. I decide to attend the event, given the fact that I was stranded.

Now, you've got to understand, Bernie and I - we’d never met before that night. But something about the way he talked, the fire in his words, it caught my attention. Bernie's going on about class conflict, economic inequality, Nixon’s tyranny, all that. At first, I'm thinking, “Here's a guy with some strong opinions.” But the more he speaks, the more I realize there's some real truth here. There's frankly a group of elitists, the puppet masters pulling the strings from behind the scenes. They've been plotting and scheming, and Nixon’s power play was the final act in their agenda to keep the working class down. Like a chess game, a game which I’m very good at by the way, and we're all just pawns there. Suddenly, everything made sense; 1964, Vietnam, the assassinations, all of it.

So, there we are, me and Bernie, standing side by side. We've witnessed the elites, led by Nixon, manipulating the system for far too long. It's time for a change, a real one. And so, after a few weeks and a few more tours around the country, we ended up in D.C. And in D.C., on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial, Bernie asked me the very words that I will never forget:

“Comrade Trump, will you lead the revolution?”
